messages.text: I can’t hear the baby anymore…
And so dark I can't see a thing.
Well, you shouldn’t be going down there!
Mom, will you cool it please?
Oh great. The light on the stairs isn’t working.
I’m fine, I’m using my cell phone light.
Geez, I haven’t been down here in a long time.
A place for people to store their junk.
So WHY would dad bring a newborn down here?!
Ugh and there’s a terrible smell!
What are you and dad keeping down here?!
I’m heading away from the smell...
I feel like I’m going to be sick.
I wish you would have waited for me.
I really didn’t want you in the basement.
I’m going to check the laundry room…
The light in here doesn’t work either.
I think I see something moving.
It’s on the floor by the washing machine.
She's swaddled in blankets but she's freezing!
Why would dad put his baby on a cold cellar floor?!????
If it means that much to you…
Put her in a safer spot and then go upstairs.
Leave her be until I get there.
I'm not leaving my sister on a concrete floor in the dark!
Maybe so but she's a human being.
She could have killed herself down here!
I’m seriously disgusted with dad’s behavior.
Don't worry about dad right now.
Who knows if dad bothered to feed her.
Jessica may hear her if you take her upstairs!
She already knows the baby is here, mom.
We really need to do something about this basement.
It’s creepy as hell and smells awful.
Close the door so the smell doesn’t get into the rest of the house.
I hope she doesn’t start crying.
I don’t need that crazy homewrecker trying to bust down the door again.
Hold on, let me see if I can find her…
She's repeating dad's name over and over.
I'm just... still a little hurt over everything.
I shouldn't take it out on you and the baby.
This can't be easy for you.
Neither of us should have to deal with this.
Hopefully Jessica will stay put until the police arrive.
I feel like it's been forever.
I know but just hang tight.
Jessica was in the kitchen window!
Then she just opened her mouth…
I ran to the attic to hide….
Your father and I have been trying to deal with it ourselves.
I'm so sorry this is now affecting you.
I don't know what to do!
I'm looking out the attic window but I can't find her…
She's not in the front or backyard.
She can't be in the house...
Maybe she's off crying somewhere again.
I'll be there in a few minutes.
Mom, I have to call the police.
Maybe they have the wrong address.
There must be something holding them up.
I think I hear footsteps on the roof!
My heart is going a mile a minute!
She shot through the attic window.
I ran downstairs and out the back door.
Now I'm hiding in the backyard.
Mom, I can't deal with this.
